
======================================================================
  PART 1: (5,6) = (2+3, 2·3) — SUM AND PRODUCT
======================================================================

For ANY two numbers a, b:
  s = a + b  (sum)
  p = a · b  (product)
  a and b are roots of z² - sz + p = 0

At (a,b) = (2,3):
  s = 5, p = 6
  z² - 5z + 6 = 0
  (z-2)(z-3) = 0  ✓

So 2 and 3 ARE THE ROOTS of z² - 5z + 6 = 0!
The polynomial z²-5z+6 with coefficients 5 and 6 ENCODES the keys.

Compare to the Fibonacci polynomial z²-z-1:
  z²-z-1: sum=1, product=-1, roots=φ,ψ
  z²-5z+6: sum=5, product=6, roots=2,3

The 'tournament polynomial' z²-5z+6 relates to Fibonacci z²-z-1:
  Replace z by z+2: (z+2)² - 5(z+2) + 6 = z² - z = z(z-1)
  So shifting by 2 turns z²-5z+6 into z²-z = z(z-1)
  Not directly Fibonacci, but close.

Discriminant of z²-5z+6: Δ = 25-24 = 1
√Δ = 1
So the 'gap' between the keys is √Δ = 1.
Compare: Fibonacci Δ = 5, Jacobsthal (z²-z-2) Δ = 9.

Companion matrix of z²-5z+6:
[[ 5 -6]
 [ 1  0]]
Eigenvalues: [np.float64(3.0), np.float64(2.0)]
= 3, 2  (the keys!) ✓

Recurrence: x(n) = 5x(n-1) - 6x(n-2)
With x(0)=0, x(1)=1: closed form x(n) = (3^n - 2^n)/(3-2) = 3^n - 2^n

  Sequence:  [0, 1, 5, 19, 65, 211, 665, 2059, 6305, 19171, 58025, 175099, 527345, 1586131, 4766585]
  = 3^n - 2^n:  [0, 1, 5, 19, 65, 211, 665, 2059, 6305, 19171, 58025, 175099, 527345, 1586131, 4766585]

With x(0)=2, x(1)=5: closed form x(n) = 3^n + 2^n
  Sequence:  [2, 5, 13, 35, 97, 275, 793, 2315, 6817, 20195, 60073, 179195, 535537, 1602515, 4799353]
  = 3^n + 2^n:  [2, 5, 13, 35, 97, 275, 793, 2315, 6817, 20195, 60073, 179195, 535537, 1602515, 4799353]

So the 'Lucas-type' for (2,3) gives: 2, 5, 13, 35, 97, ...
And the 'Fibonacci-type' for (2,3) gives: 0, 1, 5, 19, 65, 211, ...

======================================================================
  PART 2: (5,6) GENERATES (7,8)
======================================================================

Starting from 5 and 6:
  5 + 2 = 7   (adding 2)
  6 + 2 = 8   (adding 2)
  5 + 1 + 1 = 7
  6 + 1 + 1 = 8

But more structurally:
  7 = 5 + 2 = (2+3) + 2 = 2·2 + 3 = 2² + 3
  8 = 6 + 2 = (2·3) + 2 = 2³
  Also: 8 = 5 + 3 = (2+3) + 3
  Also: 7 = 6 + 1 = 2·3 + 1

In the polynomial ring Z[x] at x=2:
  5 = x + (1+x) = 2x + 1 = x² + 1
  6 = x(1+x) = x² + x
  7 = x³ - 1
  8 = x³

KEY: 6 = x(1+x) = x² + x  and  7 = x² + x + 1 = 6 + 1
So 7 = 2·3 + 1 (product of keys plus identity)

RECURRENCE CONNECTION:
  The recurrence x(n) = 5x(n-1) - 6x(n-2) with x(0)=1, x(1)=2:
  Sequence: [1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256, 512]
  = 2^n: [1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256, 512]
  So x(n) = 5x(n-1) - 6x(n-2) with x(0)=1, x(1)=2 gives POWERS OF 2!

  With x(0)=1, x(1)=3: [1, 3, 9, 27, 81, 243, 729, 2187, 6561, 19683]
  = 3^n: [1, 3, 9, 27, 81, 243, 729, 2187, 6561, 19683]
  So x(n) = 5x(n-1) - 6x(n-2) with x(0)=1, x(1)=3 gives POWERS OF 3!

THEOREM: The recurrence with coefficients (5,-6) generates both
power sequences 2^n and 3^n, because 2 and 3 are its roots.

At n=3:
  2^3 = 8 = 5·4 - 6·2 = 20-12
  3^3 = 27 = 5·9 - 6·3 = 45-18

So (5,6) literally GENERATES 8=2³ via the recurrence.
And 7 = 8-1 = 2³-1 (the Mersenne prime just below).

======================================================================
  PART 3: (5,6) IN TOURNAMENT THEORY
======================================================================

In the OCF: H = I(CG, 2)

I(CG, x) at x=5 and x=6:
  I(5) evaluates at the SUM of the keys
  I(6) evaluates at the PRODUCT of the keys

Since z²-5z+6 = (z-2)(z-3):
  I(CG, 5) = 1 + 5α₁ + 25α₂ + 125α₃ + ...
  I(CG, 6) = 1 + 6α₁ + 36α₂ + 216α₃ + ...

At n=5 (α₂=0): I(x) = 1 + α₁·x
  I(5) = 1 + 5α₁ = I(6) - α₁
  I(6) = 1 + 6α₁ = I(5) + α₁
  H = 1 + 2α₁
  I(3) = 1 + 3α₁

Relations:
  I(5) = 3H - 2      (= 3(1+2α₁)-2 = 1+6α₁... wait)
  I(5) = (5H - 3) / 2
  I(6) = (6H - 4) / 2 = 3H - 2
  I(6) = 3H - 2  ← simple!

  So I(product) = 3·I(2) - 2 = 3H - 2
  And I(sum) = (5H-3)/2

  idx=  0: H=  1, α₁=0, I(5)=1=1, I(6)=1=1
  idx= 40: H= 15, α₁=7, I(5)=36=36, I(6)=43=43
  idx=341: H= 15, α₁=7, I(5)=36=36, I(6)=43=43
  idx=500: H=  1, α₁=0, I(5)=1=1, I(6)=1=1
  idx=800: H=  5, α₁=2, I(5)=11=11, I(6)=13=13

======================================================================
  PART 4: VANDERMONDE AT (5,6)
======================================================================

From the S71d work: V(a,b) = ab(b-a) for degree-2 extraction.
  V(2,3) = 2·3·1 = 6
  V(5,6) = 5·6·1 = 30
  V(2,5) = 2·5·3 = 30
  V(2,6) = 2·6·4 = 48
  V(3,5) = 3·5·2 = 30
  V(3,6) = 3·6·3 = 54

V(2,3) = 6 = THE PRODUCT OF THE KEYS = the minimum.
V(5,6) = 30 = V(2,5) = V(3,5) = 5·6 = 5·V(2,3)

The Vandermonde at the sum/product pair (5,6) equals
5 times the Vandermonde at the original pair (2,3).
This factor of 5 = the gap between sum and product levels.

======================================================================
  PART 5: 6 = 2·3 — THE MULTIPLICATIVE BRIDGE
======================================================================

6 plays the multiplicative role that 5 plays additively:

  5 = 2 + 3  (additive combination)
  6 = 2 · 3  (multiplicative combination)

Key properties of 6:
  6 = 3! (factorial)
  6 = C(4,2) (binomial coefficient)
  6 = T₃ (3rd triangular number)
  6 is the smallest perfect number (1+2+3=6)
  6 = V(2,3) (Vandermonde determinant)

In tournament theory:
  6 = number of edges in K₄ (the 4-vertex complete graph)
  C(4,2) = 6 → tournament on 4 vertices has 6 arcs
  2⁶ = 64 = number of tournaments on 4 vertices

The (5,6) pair has a UNIQUE property:
  5 · 6 = 30
  5 + 6 = 11  ← THE DECIMAL PAIR NUMBER!

So 5 + 6 = 11 = L(5) = J(5), connecting back to the bridge!

======================================================================
  PART 6: FROM (5,6) TO (7,8)
======================================================================

The four operations from (2,3) to (7,8):

  2 + 3 = 5   →  5 + 2 = 7
  2 · 3 = 6   →  6 + 2 = 8

Both jumps are +2 (adding the first key)!

  (5, 6)  +2→  (7, 8)
  (sum, product) → (sum+2, product+2)

Or in terms of the keys:
  7 = (2+3) + 2 = 2·2 + 3 = 2² + 3
  8 = (2·3) + 2 = 2³

7 combines BOTH keys (2² + 3)
8 is PURELY the first key cubed (2³)

ALTERNATIVE: (5,6) → (7,8) via (5+2, 6+2)
  Both shifted by x=2 from the (sum,product) level

AND: 5 + 6 = 11,  7 + 8 = 15
  11 = L(5) = J(5) (the bridge)
  15 = 2⁴ - 1 = max H at n=5

  5 · 6 = 30
  7 · 8 = 56 = C(8,3) = number of 3-element subsets in 8 vertices
  Also: 56 = edges in K₈ = C(8,2)... no, C(8,2)=28.
  56 = 7·8 = C(8,3) = number of potential 3-cycles at n=8!
  At n=8, there are C(8,3) = 56 triples, each potentially a 3-cycle.

======================================================================
  PART 7: RECURRENCE HIERARCHY
======================================================================

Second-order recurrence f(n) = f(n-1) + x·f(n-2):

   x   Δ=1+4x                roots  roots rational?        field
   1        5             (1±√5)/2               no        Q(√5)
   2        9                2, -1              YES            Q
   3       13            (1±√13)/2               no       Q(√13)
   4       17            (1±√17)/2               no       Q(√17)
   5       21            (1±√21)/2               no       Q(√21)
   6       25                3, -2              YES            Q
   7       29            (1±√29)/2               no       Q(√29)
   8       33            (1±√33)/2               no       Q(√33)
   9       37            (1±√37)/2               no       Q(√37)
  10       41            (1±√41)/2               no       Q(√41)
  11       45            (1±√45)/2               no        Q(√5)
  12       49                4, -3              YES            Q

KEY PATTERN:
  x=5: Δ=21 = 3·7,  field Q(√21)
  x=6: Δ=25 = 5²,   field Q (RATIONAL! roots 3,-2)
  x=7: Δ=29,         field Q(√29)
  x=8: Δ=33 = 3·11,  field Q(√33)

x=6 is the THIRD rational point (after x=0 and x=2)!
At x=6: roots are 3 and -2. So f(n) = A·3ⁿ + B·(-2)ⁿ.
  J₆(n) = (3ⁿ - (-2)ⁿ) / 5
  L₆(n) = 3ⁿ + (-2)ⁿ

The rational points x = k(k-1): 0, 2, 6, 12, 20, 30, ...
  x=0: roots 1, 0   (trivial)
  x=2: roots 2, -1  (Jacobsthal — THE tournament level)
  x=6: roots 3, -2  (the next level — denominator 5!)
  x=12: roots 4, -3

The gap between rational points: 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, ...
  = 2k for k=1,2,3,4,5,...
  So x=2 → x=6 is a gap of 4 = 2·2
  And x=6 → x=12 is a gap of 6 = 2·3

x=6 sits EXACTLY between x=2 and x=12:
  Gap 2→6 = 4 = 2²
  Gap 6→12 = 6 = 2·3
  So the 'multiplicative bridge' 6 is also a bridge in the rational point sequence!

======================================================================
  PART 8: THE 6-SPECTRUM AND 7
======================================================================

J₆(n) = (3ⁿ - (-2)ⁿ) / 5:
  [0, 1, 1, 7, 13, 55, 133, 463, 1261, 4039, 11605, 35839, 105469, 320503, 953317]

J₆(3) = (27 + 8) / 5 = 35 / 5 = 7  ← THE TRANSITION NUMBER!
J₆(4) = (81 - 16) / 5 = 65 / 5 = 13
J₆(5) = (243 + 32) / 5 = 275 / 5 = 55 = F(10)

L₆(n) = 3ⁿ + (-2)ⁿ:
  [2, 1, 13, 19, 97, 211, 793, 2059, 6817, 19171, 60073, 175099, 535537, 1586131, 4799353]

L₆(3) = 27 - 8 = 19
L₆(4) = 81 + 16 = 97

The (5,6)-recurrence x(n) = 5x(n-1) - 6x(n-2):
  With x(0)=0, x(1)=1 → x(n) = 3ⁿ-2ⁿ
  [0, 1, 5, 19, 65, 211, 665, 2059, 6305, 19171, 58025, 175099]

x(3) = 3³-2³ = 27-8 = 19
x(4) = 3⁴-2⁴ = 81-16 = 65

Now: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ = 5·J₆(n) when n odd, and = 5·J₆(n) always?
  n=1: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ=1, J₆(n)=1, ratio=1.0000, diff=-4
  n=2: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ=5, J₆(n)=1, ratio=5.0000, diff=0
  n=3: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ=19, J₆(n)=7, ratio=2.7143, diff=-16
  n=4: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ=65, J₆(n)=13, ratio=5.0000, diff=0
  n=5: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ=211, J₆(n)=55, ratio=3.8364, diff=-64
  n=6: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ=665, J₆(n)=133, ratio=5.0000, diff=0
  n=7: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ=2059, J₆(n)=463, ratio=4.4471, diff=-256
  n=8: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ=6305, J₆(n)=1261, ratio=5.0000, diff=0
  n=9: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ=19171, J₆(n)=4039, ratio=4.7465, diff=-1024

3ⁿ-2ⁿ ≠ 5·J₆(n) in general (because (-2)ⁿ ≠ -2ⁿ for even n).
But: 3ⁿ-2ⁿ for POSITIVE 2 vs J₆ using NEGATIVE (-2).

The (5,-6) recurrence uses positive roots (2,3).
The x=6 recurrence uses roots (3,-2).
Same ABSOLUTE values, different SIGNS for the smaller root.

======================================================================
  PART 9: 7 = 2² + 3  AND  8 = 2³
======================================================================

The user's key insight: 7 = 2·2 + 3 = 2² + 3

In the polynomial ring Z[x] at x=2:
  7 = x² + (1+x) = x² + x + 1  (cyclotomic Φ₃!)
  8 = x³

Φ₃(x) = x²+x+1 = (x³-1)/(x-1)
So 7 = Φ₃(2) = (2³-1)/(2-1) = 7/1 = 7 ✓

THIS IS THE KEY: 7 is the VALUE of the 3rd cyclotomic polynomial at x=2!
  Φ₁(2) = 2-1 = 1
  Φ₂(2) = 2+1 = 3
  Φ₃(2) = 2²+2+1 = 7
  Φ₄(2) = 2²+1 = 5
  Φ₅(2) = 2⁴+2³+2²+2+1 = 31
  Φ₆(2) = 2²-2+1 = 3

So the hierarchy IS the cyclotomic evaluation at x=2!

   n     Φ_n(2)             factored   in hierarchy?
   1          1                    1             ← 1
   2          3                    3             ← 3
   3          7                    7             ← 7
   4          5                    5             ← 5
   5         31                   31                
   6          3                    3             ← 3
   7        127                  127                
   8         17                   17                
   9         73                   73                
  10         11                   11            ← 11
  11       2047                23·89                
  12         13                   13                
  13       8191                 8191                
  14         43                   43                
  15        151                  151                
  16        257                  257                
  17     131071               131071                
  18         57                 3·19                
  19     524287               524287                

THE CYCLOTOMIC DICTIONARY:
  Φ₁(2) = 1  (identity)
  Φ₂(2) = 3  (second key)
  Φ₃(2) = 7  (transition)
  Φ₄(2) = 5  (bridge = sum of keys)
  Φ₅(2) = 31 (Mersenne prime)
  Φ₆(2) = 3  (= Φ₂, composite cyclotomic)

  And 8 = 2³ = x³ is NOT cyclotomic — it's a pure power.
  7 = Φ₃(2) = cyclotomic
  8 = 2³ = exponential
  This is why (7,8) is a transition: cyclotomic meets exponential.

======================================================================
  PART 10: 2^n - 1 = PRODUCT OF CYCLOTOMIC VALUES
======================================================================

2^n - 1 = ∏_{d|n} Φ_d(2)

  2^ 1-1 =      1 = Φ_1=1 = 1 ✓
  2^ 2-1 =      3 = Φ_1=1·Φ_2=3 = 3 ✓
  2^ 3-1 =      7 = Φ_1=1·Φ_3=7 = 7 ✓
  2^ 4-1 =     15 = Φ_1=1·Φ_2=3·Φ_4=5 = 15 ✓
  2^ 5-1 =     31 = Φ_1=1·Φ_5=31 = 31 ✓
  2^ 6-1 =     63 = Φ_1=1·Φ_2=3·Φ_3=7·Φ_6=3 = 63 ✓
  2^ 7-1 =    127 = Φ_1=1·Φ_7=127 = 127 ✓
  2^ 8-1 =    255 = Φ_1=1·Φ_2=3·Φ_4=5·Φ_8=17 = 255 ✓
  2^ 9-1 =    511 = Φ_1=1·Φ_3=7·Φ_9=73 = 511 ✓
  2^10-1 =   1023 = Φ_1=1·Φ_2=3·Φ_5=31·Φ_10=11 = 1023 ✓
  2^11-1 =   2047 = Φ_1=1·Φ_11=2047 = 2047 ✓
  2^12-1 =   4095 = Φ_1=1·Φ_2=3·Φ_3=7·Φ_4=5·Φ_6=3·Φ_12=13 = 4095 ✓

At n=3: 2³-1 = 7 = Φ₁·Φ₃ = 1·7
At n=6: 2⁶-1 = 63 = Φ₁·Φ₂·Φ₃·Φ₆ = 1·3·7·3

The 6th Mersenne number 2⁶-1 = 63 = 3·3·7 = 9·7
Contains BOTH 3 and 7 as factors!
This is because 6 = 2·3, and both Φ₂(2)=3 and Φ₃(2)=7 appear.

======================================================================
  PART 11: SYNTHESIS
======================================================================


THE COMPLETE PICTURE:

(2, 3) are roots of z² - 5z + 6 = 0.
  5 = sum,  6 = product.

The recurrence x(n) = 5x(n-1) - 6x(n-2) generates:
  2ⁿ (with initial (1,2))
  3ⁿ (with initial (1,3))
  3ⁿ-2ⁿ (with initial (0,1))  
  3ⁿ+2ⁿ (with initial (2,5))

At n=3: x(3) = 2³ = 8  and  3³ = 27
  The (5,6)-recurrence generates 8 in 3 steps.

Cyclotomic structure:
  7 = Φ₃(2) = (2³-1)/(2-1) = the 3rd cyclotomic at 2
  8 = 2³ = pure power
  So (7,8) = (cyclotomic, exponential) pair.

From (5,6) to (7,8):
  5 + 2 = 7    (sum + first key = cyclotomic)
  6 + 2 = 8    (product + first key = exponential)
  Both shift by +2.

The number 6 is special:
  6 = 2·3 (product of keys)
  6 = V(2,3) (Vandermonde determinant)
  6 = 3! (factorial of second key)
  6 = C(4,2) (edges in K₄)
  
  And at x=6 in the recurrence f(n)=f(n-1)+6f(n-2):
  Roots are 3, -2 (the keys with sign flip on 2)
  J₆(3) = 7 (generates the transition number!)
  J₆(5) = 55 = F(10) (generates the doubled Fibonacci)

5 + 6 = 11 = L(5) = J(5) (the bridge to the decimal pair!)
5 · 6 = 30 = V(5,6) (the Vandermonde at sum/product level)

Everything connects through the polynomial z² - 5z + 6.

Done.
